{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lifting State Up to Share Between Components"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When two sibling components need to share the same piece of state — for example, two panels that must stay in sync about which one is active — neither component can hold that state alone. The solution is to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "lift the state up"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to the closest common ancestor, then pass the current value and a setter down as props. This creates a single source of truth that both components read from and write to."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Before and after lifting state up: duplicated state in siblings vs single source of truth in parent",
          "title": "Lifting State Up"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Problem: Sibling Components That Need to Sync"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Consider a classic accordion: only one panel should be open at a time. If each panel manages its own "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "isOpen"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " state, there is no way for clicking Panel A to close Panel B — they have no shared channel."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ Each panel owns its own state — they cannot coordinate\nfunction Panel({ title, children }) {\n  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <button onClick={() => setIsOpen(!isOpen)}>{title}</button>\n      {isOpen && <div>{children}</div>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction Accordion() {\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Panel title=\"About\">...</Panel>    {/* has its own isOpen */}\n      <Panel title=\"Skills\">...</Panel>   {/* has its own isOpen */}\n    </>\n  );\n  // Opening both at once is possible — not what an accordion should allow\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Solution: Lift State to the Common Ancestor"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Move the state variable to the parent "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Accordion"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " component. Pass the current value and the setter down to each "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Panel"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " as props. Now there is one variable in one place, and both panels share it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ✅ Accordion holds which panel is open\nfunction Accordion() {\n  const [activeIndex, setActiveIndex] = useState(null);\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Panel\n        title=\"About\"\n        isOpen={activeIndex === 0}\n        onOpen={() => setActiveIndex(0)}\n      >\n        ...\n      </Panel>\n      <Panel\n        title=\"Skills\"\n        isOpen={activeIndex === 1}\n        onOpen={() => setActiveIndex(1)}\n      >\n        ...\n      </Panel>\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\n// Panel is now a controlled component — no local state\nfunction Panel({ title, isOpen, onOpen, children }) {\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <button onClick={onOpen}>{title}</button>\n      {isOpen && <div>{children}</div>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Opening Panel B now automatically closes Panel A because "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "activeIndex"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " can only hold one value at a time. There is no synchronization code — the structure itself enforces it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Three-Step Pattern"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lifting state always follows the same three steps:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Remove"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the state from the child components."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Add"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the state to the closest common ancestor."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Pass"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the current value and setter down as props."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Worked Example: Temperature Converter"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A temperature converter with Celsius and Fahrenheit inputs is the canonical example. Both inputs must stay in sync — typing in one must update the other. Neither input can hold the canonical value because they don't know about each other."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function toCelsius(f) { return (f - 32) * 5 / 9; }\nfunction toFahrenheit(c) { return (c * 9 / 5) + 32; }\n\nfunction TemperatureInput({ scale, value, onChange }) {\n  const label = scale === 'c' ? 'Celsius' : 'Fahrenheit';\n  return (\n    <label>\n      {label}:\n      <input\n        value={value}\n        onChange={e => onChange(e.target.value)}\n      />\n    </label>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction Calculator() {\n  // Canonical state: one value in one unit\n  const [celsius, setCelsius] = useState('');\n\n  const fahrenheit = celsius !== '' ? toFahrenheit(Number(celsius)).toFixed(2) : '';\n\n  function handleCelsiusChange(val) { setCelsius(val); }\n  function handleFahrenheitChange(val) {\n    // Convert to Celsius and store — Celsius is the canonical unit\n    setCelsius(val !== '' ? toCelsius(Number(val)).toFixed(4) : '');\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <TemperatureInput scale=\"c\" value={celsius}     onChange={handleCelsiusChange} />\n      <TemperatureInput scale=\"f\" value={fahrenheit}  onChange={handleFahrenheitChange} />\n    </>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key insight: you pick "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "one canonical unit"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to store. The other is always computed from it. This prevents two state variables from diverging."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Controlled vs Uncontrolled Components"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When you lift state out of a child, the child becomes a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "controlled component"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": it receives its current value and a change handler as props, and has no local state for that value. The parent "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "controls"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " it entirely."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "table",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Uncontrolled"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableHeader",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Controlled"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Owns its state via useState"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "State lives in parent; receives value + onChange"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Parent cannot see or change it"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Parent always knows and controls current value"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Simple, self-contained"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Shareable, synced, validatable"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "tableRow",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Use when parent doesn't need it"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "tableCell",
                "attrs": {
                  "colspan": 1,
                  "rowspan": 1,
                  "colwidth": null
                },
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Use when siblings share or parent must validate"
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lift Only as High as Necessary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lift state to the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "closest"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " common ancestor that needs it. Lifting it too high means unrelated components re-render when the state changes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ BAD: lifted all the way to App even though Sidebar doesn't use activeTab\nfunction App() {\n  const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = useState('home');\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Sidebar />           {/* re-renders unnecessarily when activeTab changes */}\n      <TabBar activeTab={activeTab} onChange={setActiveTab} />\n      <TabContent tab={activeTab} />\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\n// ✅ GOOD: lift only to the component that contains TabBar and TabContent\nfunction MainArea() {\n  const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = useState('home');\n  return (\n    <>\n      <TabBar activeTab={activeTab} onChange={setActiveTab} />\n      <TabContent tab={activeTab} />\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction App() {\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Sidebar />     {/* isolated — never re-renders for tab changes */}\n      <MainArea />\n    </>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Passing Callbacks Down: the onChange Convention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When you lift state up, the child also needs a way to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "request"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " a change. The standard pattern is to pass the setter (or a wrapper around it) down as a callback prop, conventionally named "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onChange"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onSelect"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "onToggle"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", etc. The child calls the callback; the parent decides what to do with it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Parent passes a callback that wraps the setter with logic\nfunction FilterPanel({ onFilterChange }) {\n  return (\n    <select onChange={e => onFilterChange(e.target.value)}>\n      <option value=\"all\">All</option>\n      <option value=\"active\">Active</option>\n      <option value=\"done\">Done</option>\n    </select>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction TaskList() {\n  const [filter, setFilter] = useState('all');\n  const [tasks, setTasks]   = useState([...]);\n\n  const visible = tasks.filter(t =>\n    filter === 'all'    ? true :\n    filter === 'active' ? !t.done : t.done\n  );\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <FilterPanel onFilterChange={setFilter} />\n      {visible.map(t => <Task key={t.id} task={t} />)}\n    </>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The parent can add validation, logging, or transformation inside the callback before calling the setter. The child stays dumb — it just fires the event."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lifting Multiple Related Variables"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sometimes you need to lift several related state variables at once. Group them into an object when they always change together, or pass them individually when they change independently."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Lifting a position object — x and y always change together, so object makes sense\nfunction Canvas() {\n  const [position, setPosition] = useState({ x: 0, y: 0 });\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Crosshair\n        position={position}\n        onMove={setPosition}\n      />\n      <CoordDisplay position={position} />\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction Crosshair({ position, onMove }) {\n  return (\n    <div\n      style={{ transform: `translate(${position.x}px, ${position.y}px)` }}\n      onMouseMove={e => onMove({ x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY })}\n    />\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When Lifting State Is Not the Right Tool"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lifting state works well when the components that share state are close in the tree. When the common ancestor is many levels above the consumers, prop-drilling becomes painful. At that point, consider:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Context"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "createContext"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " + "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "useContext"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " lets deeply nested children read shared state without threading props through every intermediate component."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "State management libraries"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — Zustand, Redux Toolkit, Jotai, and others store global state outside the component tree."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Component composition"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — restructuring the component tree to co-locate consumers can eliminate the need to pass props through intermediate nodes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The rule of thumb: if you are passing a prop through more than two intermediate components that don't use it, it is time to reach for Context or a different structure."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common Mistakes When Lifting State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 1: Lifting state and keeping a local copy"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After lifting state to the parent, remove the corresponding "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "useState"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " from the child entirely. Keeping both creates two sources of truth that can diverge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ BAD: Panel both receives isOpen prop AND maintains its own local copy\nfunction Panel({ isOpen: isOpenProp, onOpen }) {\n  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(isOpenProp); // stale after first render!\n  // isOpen and isOpenProp will diverge when parent updates\n}\n\n// ✅ GOOD: use the prop directly, no local state\nfunction Panel({ isOpen, onOpen }) {\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <button onClick={onOpen}>Toggle</button>\n      {isOpen && <div>Content</div>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistake 2: Mutating props instead of calling the callback"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Props are read-only. A child component must never mutate a prop — it can only call the onChange callback to request a change from the parent."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// ❌ BAD: child mutates the prop object directly\nfunction Panel({ position, onMove }) {\n  function handleDrag(e) {\n    position.x = e.clientX; // mutation — React won't detect this change\n    position.y = e.clientY;\n  }\n}\n\n// ✅ GOOD: call the callback with a new object\nfunction Panel({ position, onMove }) {\n  function handleDrag(e) {\n    onMove({ x: e.clientX, y: e.clientY }); // parent updates state → re-render\n  }\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing Lifted State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When testing components that receive state as props, render the full parent (which holds the state) so the interaction goes through the real setter. Alternatively, mock the callback props for unit-level tests of the child alone."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import { render, screen, fireEvent } from '@testing-library/react';\nimport Accordion from './Accordion'; // parent that holds state\n\ntest('opening one panel closes the other', () => {\n  render(<Accordion />);\n\n  const aboutBtn  = screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'About' });\n  const skillsBtn = screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'Skills' });\n\n  fireEvent.click(aboutBtn);\n  expect(screen.getByText('About content')).toBeInTheDocument();\n  expect(screen.queryByText('Skills content')).not.toBeInTheDocument();\n\n  fireEvent.click(skillsBtn);\n  expect(screen.queryByText('About content')).not.toBeInTheDocument();\n  expect(screen.getByText('Skills content')).toBeInTheDocument();\n});\n\n// Unit test the Panel alone with a mock callback\ntest('Panel calls onOpen when button clicked', () => {\n  const onOpen = jest.fn();\n  render(<Panel title=\"About\" isOpen={false} onOpen={onOpen}>Content</Panel>);\n\n  fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: 'About' }));\n  expect(onOpen).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);\n});"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real-World Example: Shopping Cart Item Quantity"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A shopping cart header shows the total item count. Each cart row shows a quantity control. Both need to stay in sync — the header count must update when any row's quantity changes. The cart items array lives in the parent."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "jsx"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "function CartPage() {\n  const [items, setItems] = useState([\n    { id: 1, name: 'Keyboard', qty: 1, price: 79 },\n    { id: 2, name: 'Mouse',    qty: 2, price: 29 },\n  ]);\n\n  const totalQty = items.reduce((sum, i) => sum + i.qty, 0);\n\n  function setQty(id, qty) {\n    setItems(prev =>\n      prev.map(item => item.id === id ? { ...item, qty } : item)\n    );\n  }\n\n  function removeItem(id) {\n    setItems(prev => prev.filter(item => item.id !== id));\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <CartHeader count={totalQty} />   {/* reads total from shared state */}\n      <ul>\n        {items.map(item => (\n          <CartRow\n            key={item.id}\n            item={item}\n            onQtyChange={qty => setQty(item.id, qty)}\n            onRemove={()  => removeItem(item.id)}\n          />\n        ))}\n      </ul>\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction CartRow({ item, onQtyChange, onRemove }) {\n  return (\n    <li>\n      {item.name}\n      <input\n        type=\"number\" min=\"1\"\n        value={item.qty}\n        onChange={e => onQtyChange(Number(e.target.value))}\n      />\n      <button onClick={onRemove}>Remove</button>\n    </li>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction CartHeader({ count }) {\n  return <header>Cart ({count} items)</header>;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Notice that "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "CartHeader"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "CartRow"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are siblings, and both depend on "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "items"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Lifting the array to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "CartPage"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " gives both a single source of truth without any additional synchronization code."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When sibling components need to share state, move that state to their closest common ancestor."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pass the value down as a prop and a setter (or callback) down as an event prop."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The child becomes controlled — no local state for that value."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Lift only as high as necessary; lifting too high causes unrelated components to re-render."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When the common ancestor is many levels up, Context or a state management library is more practical than prop-drilling."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Never mutate props — always call the callback to request a change."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
